00:27:37.519 --> 00:27:40.490
Okay, now there are -- so
suppose you have just an

00:27:40.490 --> 00:27:45.640
arbitrary set of electrons,
and the waves coming in and

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:49.352
hitting them,
what directions will you get

00:27:49.352 --> 00:27:50.548
reinforcement in?
 

00:27:50.548 --> 00:27:54.945
Well there are two directions
that you're guaranteed,

00:27:54.945 --> 00:27:59.088
no matter what the spacing is,
and that's this.

00:27:59.088 --> 00:28:04.308
Here the light comes in and
goes out.

00:28:04.308 --> 00:28:08.348
So the direct beam,
you have the same path,

00:28:08.348 --> 00:28:11.450
because one of them gets hit
earlier,

00:28:11.450 --> 00:28:14.953
but has a longer path coming
out, and the other one gets hit

00:28:14.953 --> 00:28:17.450
later but has a shorter path
coming out.

00:28:17.450 --> 00:28:20.538
So they're guaranteed to be
exactly in-phase if they're

00:28:20.538 --> 00:28:22.140
scattering straight ahead.
 

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:23.278
Okay?
 

00:28:23.278 --> 00:28:26.549
But only a little of the light
is getting scattered.

00:28:26.549 --> 00:28:28.108
Most of it is the direct beam.
 

00:28:28.108 --> 00:28:32.349
So you don't even notice the
difference, from that.

00:28:32.349 --> 00:28:34.288
So that's not very exciting.
 

00:28:34.288 --> 00:28:39.088
But there's another angle at
which you're sure that these two

00:28:39.088 --> 00:28:43.089
are going to be in-phase,
and that's this angle.

00:28:43.089 --> 00:28:48.328
Now how do we get to that angle?
 

00:28:48.328 --> 00:28:52.410
I've lost some of the -- since
you downloaded it there's some

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:54.108
more stuff in here now.
 

00:28:54.108 --> 00:28:57.088
But -- so now I can't quite
remember, let me just try.

00:28:57.088 --> 00:29:01.721
Okay, so this blue line here is
called the scattering vector,

00:29:01.721 --> 00:29:06.042
and that's how different the
arrow coming out is from the

00:29:06.042 --> 00:29:07.509
arrow going in.
 

00:29:07.509 --> 00:29:08.990
Right?
 

00:29:08.990 --> 00:29:11.839
That's just a funny
mathematical or geometric thing

00:29:11.839 --> 00:29:15.046
that people have defined;
they call it the scattering

00:29:15.046 --> 00:29:15.539
vector.
 

00:29:15.539 --> 00:29:16.269
Right?
 

00:29:16.269 --> 00:29:21.348
Now this length is exactly the
same as that length.

00:29:21.348 --> 00:29:24.450
This length is exactly the same
as that length,

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:26.640
and when you turn at a given
angle,

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:29.489
those two will -- the vector
between those will be

00:29:29.489 --> 00:29:32.279
perpendicular to the direction
they're going,

00:29:32.279 --> 00:29:33.829
and they'll be in-phase again.
 

00:29:33.829 --> 00:29:35.618
Right?
 

00:29:35.618 --> 00:29:40.240
And if you draw the line that
connects the two points,

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:45.558
notice the scattering vector is
perpendicular to that line.

00:29:45.558 --> 00:29:53.336
So you say that this incoming
wave was scattered perpendicular

00:29:53.336 --> 00:29:55.250
to this line.
 

00:29:55.250 --> 00:29:57.009
That's how a mirror works.
 

00:29:57.009 --> 00:30:00.068
Right?
 

00:30:00.068 --> 00:30:04.364
That angle is called the
specular angle,

00:30:04.364 --> 00:30:09.500
because speculum is the
Latin word for mirror.

00:30:09.500 --> 00:30:12.019
Right?
 

00:30:12.019 --> 00:30:15.977
So you're bound to get
reinforcement at the specular

00:30:15.977 --> 00:30:20.400
angle, and you know that from
having looked at mirrors.

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:25.077
Okay, now suppose there were
another electron on that same

00:30:25.077 --> 00:30:26.390
line or plane.
 

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:27.278
Okay?
 

00:30:27.278 --> 00:30:30.808
For the same reason it's
guaranteed to be in-phase.

00:30:30.808 --> 00:30:34.915
So everything on that plane
will scatter in-phase at that

00:30:34.915 --> 00:30:36.308
particular angle.
 

00:30:36.308 --> 00:30:38.529
They'll all reinforce one
another.

00:30:38.529 --> 00:30:40.558
Great.
 

00:30:40.558 --> 00:30:46.170
So all electrons on a plane
perpendicular to the scattering

00:30:46.170 --> 00:30:50.910
vector, scatter in-phase at the
specular angle.

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:53.873
Now suppose you have a whole
bunch of electrons and you have

00:30:53.873 --> 00:30:56.737
to figure out how they're going
to reinforce or cancel one

00:30:56.737 --> 00:30:57.339
another.
 

00:30:57.339 --> 00:30:59.410
There's a trick you can use.
 

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:05.868
You see if you can discern a
set of planes that are evenly

00:31:05.868 --> 00:31:10.288
spaced, that contain all,
or almost all,

00:31:10.288 --> 00:31:15.048
of the electrons you're
interested in.

00:31:15.048 --> 00:31:18.239
Okay, now if you look at this
pattern, you can see that

00:31:18.239 --> 00:31:20.542
there's a set of planes,
equally spaced,

00:31:20.542 --> 00:31:22.670
that passes through all of
them.

00:31:22.670 --> 00:31:24.319
Can you perceive it?
 

00:31:24.319 --> 00:31:27.920
There.
 

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:30.163
Okay, there are three electrons
on the first plane,

00:31:30.163 --> 00:31:32.405
four on the second,
two on the third and one on the

00:31:32.405 --> 00:31:32.900
fourth.
 

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:34.470
Okay?
 

00:31:34.470 --> 00:31:40.318
Now why is that handy?
 

00:31:40.318 --> 00:31:44.097
Okay, so there's the scattering
vector, perpendicular to these

00:31:44.097 --> 00:31:47.691
planes, and all the electrons on
any one plane will scatter

00:31:47.691 --> 00:31:49.548
in-phase with one another.
 

00:31:49.548 --> 00:31:53.721
Okay, so it's as if there were
a single electron three times

00:31:53.721 --> 00:31:55.856
bigger,
or four or two or one,

00:31:55.856 --> 00:31:59.069
on those successive planes,
because they're all going to be

00:31:59.069 --> 00:32:00.230
in-phase with one another.
 

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:03.403
So we could pretend they're all
at one point,

00:32:03.403 --> 00:32:04.920
on any given plane.
 

00:32:04.920 --> 00:32:05.490
Okay?
 

00:32:05.490 --> 00:32:09.836
So now all we have to worry
about is the phase relationship

00:32:09.836 --> 00:32:12.009
from one plane to the next.
 

00:32:12.009 --> 00:32:14.528
Got that?
 

00:32:14.528 --> 00:32:17.618
If they were in-phase from one
plane to the next,

00:32:17.618 --> 00:32:20.744
as well as on the planes,
then everything will be

00:32:20.744 --> 00:32:24.717
in-phase and you'll get really
bright reflection coming out at

00:32:24.717 --> 00:32:26.410
that scattering angle.
 

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:27.318
Okay?
 

00:32:27.318 --> 00:32:31.324
Now, so let's think -- so it's
as if we had these collected

00:32:31.324 --> 00:32:35.327
electrons all lying on the
scattering vector and we want to

00:32:35.327 --> 00:32:38.848
know whether they're in-phase
with one another.

00:32:38.848 --> 00:32:42.846
Okay, so here's light that
comes in and out at a certain

00:32:42.846 --> 00:32:46.338
angle from the first one;
three electrons worth of

00:32:46.338 --> 00:32:49.336
scattering from that,
the ones that were on that

00:32:49.336 --> 00:32:50.420
plane -- okay?
 

00:32:50.420 --> 00:32:52.130
-- and four from the second
plane.

00:32:52.130 --> 00:32:55.710
Now are the three and the four
in-phase with one another?

00:32:55.710 --> 00:32:59.580
What condition would have to
apply in order for those to be

00:32:59.580 --> 00:33:01.450
in-phase with one another?
 

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:06.630
They have different path
lengths, but if the paths differ

00:33:06.630 --> 00:33:10.328
by an integral number of
wavelengths,

00:33:10.328 --> 00:33:13.410
then they'll be in-phase with
one another and reinforce.

00:33:13.410 --> 00:33:14.220
Okay?
 

00:33:14.220 --> 00:33:19.598
So there's the path difference
in red.

00:33:19.598 --> 00:33:22.847
If that happens to be --
suppose the wavelength of the

00:33:22.847 --> 00:33:24.980
light,
and the angle of the scattering

00:33:24.980 --> 00:33:27.430
-- which also determines that
path difference,

00:33:27.430 --> 00:33:31.970
as you can see -- suppose that
the wavelength and the angle are

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:35.338
such that that happens to be one
wavelength?

00:33:35.338 --> 00:33:38.160
Okay, so those are in-phase
with one another;

00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:40.579
all seven will be scattering
together.

00:33:40.579 --> 00:33:42.450
Right?
 

00:33:42.450 --> 00:33:46.111
How about the next one,
with two electrons,

00:33:46.111 --> 00:33:48.029
how about its phase?
 

00:33:48.029 --> 00:33:52.448
What was the condition we
talked about,

00:33:52.448 --> 00:33:54.890
up here at the top?
 

00:33:54.890 --> 00:33:55.569
Student:  Evenly.
 

00:33:55.569 --> 00:33:56.368
Prof: Evenly spaced.
 

00:33:56.368 --> 00:33:59.970
So what do you know about the
next one?

00:33:59.970 --> 00:34:00.430
Student: 
&gt;

00:34:00.430 --> 00:34:03.704
Prof: It's going to be
in-phase too,

00:34:03.704 --> 00:34:06.279
two waves behind the first one.
 

00:34:06.279 --> 00:34:07.608
Right?
 

00:34:07.608 --> 00:34:10.226
It'll be two wavelengths behind
the first one,

00:34:10.226 --> 00:34:11.679
exactly, at some angle.
 

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:12.630
Right?
 

00:34:12.630 --> 00:34:16.789
And the next one will be three
wavelengths behind.

00:34:16.789 --> 00:34:20.059
So all these electrons are
going to be scattering in-phase

00:34:20.059 --> 00:34:21.610
at that particular angle.
 

00:34:21.610 --> 00:34:24.219
So you get a really strong
reflection coming out.

00:34:24.219 --> 00:34:24.949
Right?
 

00:34:24.949 --> 00:34:30.829
It'll be as if it were all the
electrons working together.

00:34:30.829 --> 00:34:34.465
So the net in-phase scattering
is as if there were ten

00:34:34.465 --> 00:34:36.730
electrons doing the scattering.
 

00:34:36.730 --> 00:34:38.550
That's great, right?
 

00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:42.161
Now suppose that the first path
difference, instead -- suppose

00:34:42.161 --> 00:34:45.360
you had a different wavelength
or a different angle.

00:34:45.360 --> 00:34:48.483
So the first,
between the three and the four,

00:34:48.483 --> 00:34:52.389
suppose the difference in path
was half a wavelength.

00:34:52.389 --> 00:34:53.760
Then how would it differ?
 

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:56.170
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:34:56.170 --> 00:34:57.969
Prof: How about between
the first and the second.

00:34:57.969 --> 00:34:58.320
Wilson?
 

00:34:58.320 --> 00:34:59.170
Student:  Cancel.
 

00:34:59.170 --> 00:35:00.000
Student:  The first and
the second?

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:01.443
Prof: The first and the
second, would they exactly

00:35:01.443 --> 00:35:02.010
cancel and get zero?
 

00:35:02.010 --> 00:35:03.440
Student:  There'd be one
left.

00:35:03.440 --> 00:35:04.389
Prof: Why?
 

00:35:04.389 --> 00:35:05.751
Student: There's one --
Prof: Ah,

00:35:05.751 --> 00:35:08.469
there are three in the first
and four in the second,

00:35:08.469 --> 00:35:08.949
right?
 

00:35:08.949 --> 00:35:15.530
So you got plus three but minus
four.

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:18.010
How about the next one?
 

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:19.420
Speak up gang.
 

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:20.010
Students:  Plus two.
 

00:35:20.010 --> 00:35:21.929
Prof: Plus two.
 

00:35:21.929 --> 00:35:22.929
And the last one?
 

00:35:22.929 --> 00:35:23.639
Students:  Minus one.
 

00:35:23.639 --> 00:35:24.519
Prof: Minus one.
 

00:35:24.519 --> 00:35:26.250
And what's the net scattering?
 

00:35:26.250 --> 00:35:26.940
Student:  Nothing.
 

00:35:26.940 --> 00:35:29.010
Students:  Zero.
 

00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:30.510
Prof: Zero.
 

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:32.210
Okay?
 

00:35:32.210 --> 00:35:34.710
So you can see how this is a
